节 brief / continuity review 抽成 skill\n53:   - 为 task-hall 发布一组标准化子任务模板\n\n(End of file - total 53 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# 任务报告\n\n## 任务结论\n\n完成\n\n## 完成内容\n\n- 产出了一份面向多 agent 协作的玄幻小说写作工作流 Markdown 方案文档。\n- 文档覆盖了工作流目标与适用范围、agent 角色划分与职责边界、阶段流程图与步骤清单。\n- 文档明确给出了各阶段的输入、输出、质量门槛。\n- 文档明确标注了哪些步骤适合并行执行、哪些步骤必须串行推进。\n- 文档设计了长篇一致性资产集，覆盖世界观 bible、角色卡、伏笔表、时间线、术语表、continuity 日志等。\n- 文档包含正文生成前、中、后的质量控制机制，以及 review / repair / canon 更新闭环。\n- 文档提供了可直接复用的关键提示词模板，包括立项、世界观、分卷规划、章节 brief、正文写作、continuity review、canon 更新等。\n- 文档给出了面向 task-hall 的任务拆分建议，并为每类后续任务说明了目标、交付物、验证方式和领取门槛。\n- 文档给出了落地到 `mycli agent-workflow` 与 `skill-library` 的具体建议，包括推荐工程结构、step 设计、输入输出模式与 skill 拆分方向。\n\n## 未完成内容\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"agent_workspace\\tmp\\task_20260425_020706_ca7376_report.md","time":{"start":1777057477136,"end":1777057477146}},"id":"prt_dc0e1320c001gYzDagcTD2XGJI","sessionID":"ses_23f228ff5ffeiKfbDbSH2OaYg8","messageID":"msg_dc0e10c9a0019B6CAUX93qE5zn"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777057477177,"sessionID":"ses_23f228ff5ffeiKfbDbSH2OaYg8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_MjxZMAN2p61LITbCvGApUNP3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"D:\\agent_workspace\\capability-library\\skill-library\\opencode-capability-skill\\SKILL.md","limit":220,"offset":1},"output":"<path>D:\\agent_workspace\\capability-library\\skill-library\\opencode-capability-skill\\SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: opencode-capability-skill\n3: description: OpenCode capability playbook for turning OpenCode into a reusable engineering workflow. Use when operating OpenCode via CLI, designing agents, attaching rule files as pseudo-skills, choosing models, debugging capability gaps, or building scripted coding/review/architecture workflows around OpenCode.\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # OpenCode Capability Skill\n7: \n8: This skill is a practical operating guide for using OpenCode as a scriptable engineering runtime rather than a one-off chat tool.\n9: \n10: Use this skill when you need to:\n11: - drive OpenCode from CLI instead of manual UI steps\n12: - choose between `run`, `serve`, `web`, `attach`, `agent`, `debug`, `providers`, `models`, `mcp`, and session commands\n13: - design reusable agents and place them in the correct directory\n14: - use rule files as task inputs when native skill loading is unavailable\n15: - work around model, permission, or environment limitations\n16: - build reliable OpenCode workflows with explicit verification\n17: \n18: ## Operating assumptions\n19: \n20: - Prefer CLI-first usage. The main conclusion from the source notes is that OpenCode's core capabilities can be driven by command parameters and embedded into scripts, CI, IDE actions, and automation.\n21: - Treat natural-language final reports as potentially incomplete. Require artifact checks, file checks, command output checks, or tests.\n22: - Distinguish between:\n23:   - native OpenCode agents\n24:   - plugin-layer agents\n25:   - native skills\n26:   - attached rule files used like skills\n27: - Use one of the two confirmed auto-discovery locations for native agent files:\n28:   - `<project>/.opencode/agent/*.md`\n29:   - `C:\\Users\\38188\\.config\\opencode\\agent\\*.md`\n30: - Do not assume arbitrary custom directories such as `.opencode-test-native/agent/` will be auto-discovered.\n31: - Assume external skill directories may be blocked by permission rules unless passed in as attached files.\n32: \n33: ## Core workflow\n34: \n35: 1. Identify the task shape.\n36: 2. Pick the right OpenCode entrypoint.\n37: 3. Pick model, agent, session, and working directory explicitly.\n38: 4. If native skill loading is unavailable, attach a rule file with `-f`.\n39: 5. Execute in the smallest reliable loop.\n40: 6. Verify outputs with files, command results, or tests instead of trusting the summary.\n41: \n42: ## Task routing\n43: \n44: - For one-shot execution or automation: read `references/cli-workflows.md`.\n45: - For command catalog and capability lookup: read `references/cli-capabilities.md`.\n46: - For agent design, placement, and validation: read `references/agent-system.md`.\n47: - For model, permission, and skill limitations: read `references/constraints-and-validation.md`.\n48: - For reusable native agent starter files: read `templates/README.md` and copy from `templates/agents/`.\n49: \n50: ## Default rules\n51: \n52: - Prefer `opencode run` for scripted and repeatable tasks.\n53: - Prefer explicit `--dir`, `--agent`, and `--model` instead of relying on defaults.\n54: - Prefer `.opencode/agent/` for project-specific agents and `C:\\Users\\38188\\.config\\opencode\\agent\\` for global reusable agents.\n55: - Prefer attached rule files over assuming native skill discovery works.\n56: - Prefer verification commands and artifact inspection after every non-trivial task.\n57: - If a task is high-risk, avoid `--dangerously-skip-permissions` unless the environment is fully trusted.\n58: \n59: ## Registering custom tools vs loading skills\n60: \n61: Keep these mechanisms separate:\n62: \n63: - Custom tools are registered through the plugin layer, not through `SKILL.md` frontmatter.\n64: - Native agent files control which tools an agent is allowed to use, but do not define new tools.\n65: - Skills mainly inject instructions and workflow rules into the session. They tell the model when and why to use a tool.\n66: - If native skill loading is unreliable, attach `SKILL.md` with `-f` and treat it as a rule file.\n67: \n68: Practical model:\n69: \n70: 1. Register a custom tool in a plugin.\n71: 2. Make sure the chosen agent can use that tool.\n72: 3. Load or attach a skill so the model knows when to call the tool.\n73: \n74: ### Verified local custom tool registration example\n75: \n76: The following pattern was validated in the local environment by registering and executing a `hello_tool` plugin from `C:\\Users\\38188\\.config\\opencode\\hello-tool`.\n77: \n78: Plugin package shape:\n79: \n80: ```json\n81: {\n82:   \"name\": \"opencode-hello-tool\",\n83:   \"version\": \"0.0.1\",\n84:   \"type\": \"module\",\n85:   \"main\": \"./index.js\",\n86:   \"dependencies\": {\n87:     \"@opencode-ai/plugin\": \"1.14.17\"\n88:   }\n89: }\n90: ```\n91: \n92: Plugin implementation shape:\n93: \n94: ```js\n95: import { tool } from \"@opencode-ai/plugin\";\n96: \n97: /** @type {import(\"@opencode-ai/plugin\").Plugin} */\n98: const HelloToolPlugin = async () => {\n99:   return {\n100:     tool: {\n101:       hello_tool: tool({\n102:         description: \"Return a hello message for tool registration testing\",\n103:         args: {\n104:           name: tool.schema.string().default(\"world\"),\n105:         },\n106:         async execute(args, context) {\n107:           const output = `hello, ${args.name} from ${context.directory}`;\n108:           context.metadata({\n109:             title: \"hello tool test\",\n110:             metadata: {\n111:               tool: \"hello_tool\",\n112:               name: args.name,\n113:             },\n114:           });\n115:           return {\n116:             output,\n117:             metadata: {\n118:               ok: true,\n119:             },\n120:           };\n121:         },\n122:       }),\n123:     },\n124:   };\n125: };\n126: \n127: export default HelloToolPlugin;\n128: ```\n129: \n130: Config entry shape in `opencode.jsonc`:\n131: \n132: ```json\n133: {\n134:   \"plugin\": [\n135:     \"oh-my-openagent\",\n136:     \"./hello-tool\"\n137:   ]\n138: }\n139: ```\n140: \n141: This confirms that a relative local plugin path under `C:\\Users\\38188\\.config\\opencode` can be loaded by OpenCode in this environment.\n142: \n143: ### Verified custom tool execution test\n144: \n145: The following command successfully caused OpenCode to call `hello_tool` and return the tool output:\n146: \n147: ```bash\n148: opencode run \"Call the hello_tool with name='tester'. If the tool is available, use it and print only the tool result.\" --dir \"C:\\Users\\38188\" --format json\n149: ```\n150: \n151: Expected result pattern:\n152: \n153: - tool call name is `hello_tool`\n154: - tool input includes `name: tester`\n155: - tool output is `hello, tester from C:\\Users\\38188`\n156: \n157: ### How to bring a skill into the same workflow\n158: \n159: Use a skill to provide execution policy, not to define the tool itself.\n160: \n161: Typical pattern:\n162: \n163: 1. Register the tool through a plugin.\n164: 2. Enable or allow the tool for the target agent.\n165: 3. Attach a `SKILL.md` file with `-f` so the model is instructed to use the tool in the right situations.\n166: \n167: Example:\n168: \n169: ```bash\n170: opencode run \"先读取我附带的规则文件，再执行任务；如果需要打招呼测试，优先调用 hello_tool\" --dir D:\\path\\to\\project -f D:\\path\\to\\SKILL.md\n171: ```\n172: \n173: Important distinction:\n174: \n175: - plugin answers: what executable capability exists\n176: - agent answers: which role may use that capability\n177: - skill answers: when the model should use that capability\n178: \n179: ## Minimal command patterns\n180: \n181: ```bash\n182: opencode run \"检查当前项目结构\" --dir D:\\path\\to\\project\n183: opencode run \"修复当前目录里的启动错误并验证\" --dir D:\\path\\to\\project --agent coder -m custom-aiapi-meccy-top/gpt-5.4\n184: opencode run \"先读取我附带的规则文件，再执行任务\" --dir D:\\path\\to\\project -f D:\\path\\to\\SKILL.md\n185: opencode agent list\n186: opencode debug agent coder\n187: opencode models --verbose\n188: opencode debug skill\n189: ```\n190: \n191: ## Included reusable assets\n192: \n193: This skill includes native OpenCode agent templates for:\n194: - `coder`\n195: - `reviewer`\n196: - `architect`\n197: \n198: Use them by copying the relevant `.md` file into:\n199: \n200: ```text\n201: <project>/.opencode/agent/\n202: ```\n203: \n204: Or into the global directory for cross-project reuse:\n205: \n206: ```text\n207: C:\\Users\\38188\\.config\\opencode\\agent\\\n208: ```\n209: \n210: Then validate with:\n211: \n212: ```bash\n213: opencode agent list\n214: opencode debug agent coder\n215: opencode run --agent coder \"解释当前项目结构\"\n216: ```\n217: \n218: ## Known practical conclusions\n219: \n220: - OpenCode can be used as a commandable capability layer, not just an interactive TUI.\n\n(Showing lines 1-220 of 235. Use offset=221 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: opencode-capability-skill\ndescription: OpenCode capability playbook for turning OpenCode into a reusable engineering workflow. Use when operating OpenCode via CLI, designing agents, attaching rule files as pseudo-skills, choosing models, debugging capability gaps, or building scripted coding/review/architecture workflows around OpenCode.\n---\n\n# OpenCode Capability Skill\n\nThis skill is a practical operating guide for using OpenCode as a scriptable engineering runtime rather than a one-off chat tool.\n\nUse this skill when you need to:\n- drive OpenCode from CLI instead of manual UI steps\n- choose between `run`, `serve`, `web`, `attach`, `agent`, `debug`, `providers`, `models`, `mcp`, and session commands\n- design reusable agents and place them in the correct directory\n- use rule files as task inputs when native skill loading is unavailable\n- work around model, permission, or environment limitations\n- build reliable OpenCode workflows with explicit verification\n\n## Operating assumptions\n\n- Prefer CLI-first usage. The main conclusion from the source notes is that OpenCode's core capabilities can be driven by command parameters and embedded into scripts, CI, IDE actions, and automation.","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":"agent_workspace\\capability-library\\skill-library\\opencode-capability-skill\\SKILL.md","time":{"start":1777057477165,"end":1777057477176}},"id":"prt_dc0e13210002tNi7sI3bSIt0VH","sessionID":"ses_23f228ff5ffeiKfbDbSH2OaYg8","messageID":"msg_dc0e10c9a0019B6CAUX93qE5zn"}}
