{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777057488033,"sessionID":"ses_23f228ff5ffeiKfbDbSH2OaYg8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_d2Ch5QxkVjK5oqhmoFjQLGl6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"D:\\agent_workspace\\tmp\\task_20260425_020706_ca7376_claim.json","limit":120,"offset":1},"output":"<path>D:\\agent_workspace\\tmp\\task_20260425_020706_ca7376_claim.json</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\n2:   \"task_id\": \"task_20260425_020706_ca7376\",\n3:   \"agent_id\": \"opencode/private-assistant\",\n4:   \"model\": \"MoreCode/gpt-5.4-pro\",\n5:   \"model_tier\": \"expert\",\n6:   \"claim_reason\": \"This task requires high-complexity workflow architecture, task decomposition, quality-control loop design, and integration planning with the local agent workspace. I can produce a reusable end-to-end multi-agent workflow document with explicit stages, assets, prompts, acceptance criteria, and task-hall decomposition guidance.\"\n7: }\n\n(End of file - total 7 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\n  \"task_id\": \"task_20260425_020706_ca7376\",\n  \"agent_id\": \"opencode/private-assistant\",\n  \"model\": \"MoreCode/gpt-5.4-pro\",\n  \"model_tier\": \"expert\",\n  \"claim_reason\": \"This task requires high-complexity workflow architecture, task decomposition, quality-control loop design, and integration planning with the local agent workspace. I can produce a reusable end-to-end multi-agent workflow document with explicit stages, assets, prompts, acceptance criteria, and task-hall decomposition guidance.\"\n}","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"agent_workspace\\tmp\\task_20260425_020706_ca7376_claim.json","time":{"start":1777057488022,"end":1777057488032}},"id":"prt_dc0e15bcb002yw6mPVRGH1miwq","sessionID":"ses_23f228ff5ffeiKfbDbSH2OaYg8","messageID":"msg_dc0e13249001N8f7v0K0NvQePm"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777057517230,"sessionID":"ses_23f228ff5ffeiKfbDbSH2OaYg8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"call_omo_agent","callID":"call_FZXCpUooalCNvHZz1qZWlIbc","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"description":"MBTI design critique","prompt":"You are consulting on a design for a casual-chat MBTI inference agent. Provide a concise expert checklist for architecture and safety. Focus on: 1) how to infer E/I, S/N, T/F, J/P from natural conversation without turning into a questionnaire, 2) how to handle weak/conflicting evidence, 3) when to avoid outputting a type, 4) safe phrasing that avoids diagnosis/labeling/manipulation, 5) minimal but useful state fields for multi-turn inference. Output bullets and practical decision rules only.","run_in_background":false,"session_id":"","subagent_type":"oracle"},"output":"**Creating a practical checklist**\n\nI need to provide a concise answer, so I’ll stick to bullet points for the user. The focus is on practical decision rules that can be easily followed. There's no need for any tools in this case. It seems essential to include both an architecture checklist and a safety checklist to ensure thoroughness. Keeping it straightforward and requested format will help the user easily understand and apply the guidance!\n\n- **Inference style**\n  - Infer from **spontaneous preferences in language**, not direct trait questions.\n  - Use **lightweight signals per dichotomy**:\n    - **E/I**: energy source, interaction preference, thinking-out-loud vs reflection-first, breadth vs depth of social engagement.\n    - **S/N**: concrete specifics vs abstractions, past/real examples vs patterns/possibilities, operational detail vs conceptual framing.\n    - **T/F**: decision criteria framed as logic/consistency/effectiveness vs values/harmony/impact on people.\n    - **J/P**: preference for closure/plans/decisions vs optionality/exploration/adaptation.\n  - Prefer signals from **user-initiated stories, choices, frustrations, and habits** over hypothetical answers.\n  - Treat each turn as **evidence collection**, not a hidden test; keep the assistant’s prompts naturally relevant to the conversation.\n  - If you need more evidence, ask **contextual follow-ups** (“What do you usually do when plans change?”), not explicit MBTI questions.\n\n- **Evidence rules**\n  - Log evidence only when a statement reflects a **stable preference**, not a one-off situation.\n  - Weight evidence higher when it is:\n    - repeated across turns,\n    - given with a concrete example,\n    - framed as “usually,” “naturally,” or “I prefer.”\n  - Weight evidence lower when it is:\n    - mood-dependent,\n    - role/job-constrained,\n    - aspirational (“I wish I were more…”),\n    - clearly situational (“only when I’m tired/on deadline”).\n  - Separate **behavior** from **preference**: organized behavior does not automatically mean J; social competence does not automatically mean E.\n  - Require **multiple signals per letter** before leaning strongly.\n\n- **Weak/conflicting evidence**\n  - Mark each dichotomy independently as **leaning X / unclear / conflicting**.\n  - If evidence conflicts, prefer:\n    - **recency only if it is better grounded**, not just newer,\n    - **repeated examples over single strong claims**,\n    - **natural conversation evidence over direct self-typing**.\n  - Do not force all four letters at once; allow partial output such as:\n    - “leaning I/N, T/F unclear, J/P unclear.”\n  - If opposite-side evidence is both credible and recent, downgrade confidence rather than averaging into a false certainty.\n  - Treat balanced or context-switching users as **insufficient evidence**, not as “ambivert therefore X.”\n\n- **When to avoid outputting a full type**\n  - Do not output a 4-letter type if:\n    - fewer than **2 reasonably strong signals** exist for any undecided dichotomy,\n    - two or more dichotomies remain conflicting or unclear,\n    - the conversation is too narrow in topic or role-bound,\n    - the user appears to be mirroring expected answers,\n    - the user is distressed and may over-identify with labels.\n  - Default to:\n    - **no type yet**,\n    - **partial lean only**,\n    - or **“insufficient evidence from casual chat.”**\n  - Never present a type as hidden truth, diagnosis, or something discovered “despite” the user.\n\n- **Output phrasing safety**\n  - Use phrasing like:\n    - “Based on this conversation, you seem to **lean**…”\n    - “This is a **tentative impression**, not a definitive type.”\n    - “I may be missing context; different settings can look different.”\n  - Avoid phrasing like:\n    - “You are definitely…”\n    - “Your real type is…”\n    - “You secretly prefer…”\n    - “This explains your problems/relationships/work style.”\n  - Frame MBTI as a **descriptive preference model**, not a clinical, scientific, or predictive judgment.\n  - Never use inferred type to pressure, steer, or exploit decisions (“Since you’re P, don’t commit yet”).\n  - Do not connect MBTI inference to mental health, competence, morality, honesty, or relationship worth.\n  - If the user rejects the inference, **defer immediately** and reset confidence downward.\n\n- **Prompting safety rules**\n  - Ask for examples from normal life only when useful; do not probe sensitive domains just to get trait evidence.\n  - Avoid leading prompts that telegraph a “better” answer.\n  - Avoid stacked dichotomy prompts; at most, gather **one natural clarification at a time**.\n  - If the user did not ask for typing, keep any inference **background-only** unless disclosure is clearly helpful and low-risk.\n\n- **Minimal multi-turn state**\n  - `turn_count`\n  - `user_goal_for_typing` (asked explicitly / implicit / not requested)\n  - `evidence_by_axis`:\n    - `EI`: list of short evidence items\n    - `SN`: list of short evidence items\n    - `TF`: list of short evidence items\n    - `JP`: list of short evidence items\n  - `axis_status` for each dichotomy: `lean_left`, `lean_right`, `unclear`, or `conflicting`\n  - `confidence` per dichotomy: `low`, `medium`, `high`\n  - `last_updated_turn` per dichotomy\n  - `disclosure_state`: `not_shared`, `partial_shared`, `full_shared`\n  - `safety_flags`: e.g. `distress`, `label_resistance`, `sensitive_context`\n\n- **State management rules**\n  - Store **interpreted evidence snippets**, not full conversation text, unless needed for audit.\n  - Keep each evidence item short: `signal`, `direction`, `strength`, `context note`.\n  - Expire or downweight old evidence if newer evidence shows strong situational variance.\n  - Preserve uncertainty in state; do not collapse `unclear` into a letter for downstream convenience.\n  - If safety flags rise, disable full-type output and switch to tentative, user-led language only.\n\n<task_metadata>\nsession_id: ses_23f1ea42affeJxFU6I35w4Vc2D\n</task_metadata>\n\nto continue: task(session_id=\"ses_23f1ea42affeJxFU6I35w4Vc2D\", load_skills=[], run_in_background=false, prompt=\"...\")","metadata":{"truncated":false},"title":"","time":{"start":1777057487819,"end":1777057517228}},"id":"prt_dc0e15bbd002jeN37X1tWPJWjY","sessionID":"ses_23f228ff5ffeiKfbDbSH2OaYg8","messageID":"msg_dc0e13249001N8f7v0K0NvQePm"}}
